a Tusitala Marsh, ku‘ualoha ho‘omanawanui, Craig Santos Perez, Gregory Clark, Chelle Pahinui, Dan Taulapapa McMullin, Michael Puleloa, Lisa King, and Steven Gin. Collectively, their words guide us over ocean routes like the great wa‘a, va‘a, waka, proa, and sakman once navigated by the ancestors of Oceania, now navigated again by their descendants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAestheticsxPolitical aspectszOceania. 0aAestheticsxSocial aspectszOceania. 0aRhetoriczOceania. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aCarroll, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Jeffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevatine, Flora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGin, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh, Selina Tusitala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDougall, Brandy Nālani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDougall, Brandy Nālani, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcMullin, Dan Taulapapa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordstrom, Georganne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordstrom, Georganne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOsorio, Jonathan Kay Kamakawiwo‘ole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPahinui, Chelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerez, Craig Santos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aP